ğŸ”¹ FX OPTION (Business Product)
What it is
Gives right (not obligation) to exchange currency at fixed rate
Customer decides whether to use it

Key Points
Premium paid upfront
Maximum loss = premium
Settlement only if exercised
Used for hedging FX risk

Lifecycle
Booked â†’ Active â†’ Waiting â†’ Exercised / Expired â†’ Closed

Money Flow
Booking â†’ Premium posted
Exercise â†’ Currency exchange
Expiry (no exercise) â†’ No settlement
One-Line Rule

FX Option = Choice + Premium + Limited Risk

ğŸ”¹ ETD (Exchange-Traded Derivative)
What it is
Standardized contract traded on exchange
Mandatory settlement

Key Points
No premium
Margin required
Daily MTM (Mark-to-Market)
Loss can be unlimited

Lifecycle
Trade â†’ Daily MTM â†’ Margin Calls â†’ Settlement â†’ Close

Money Flow
Daily profit/loss settled
Margin adjusted every day
Final settlement is compulsory

One-Line Rule
ETD = Obligation + Daily P&L + Mandatory Settlement

ğŸ”¹ FXPM (FX Product Management)
What it is
NOT a product
Core processing engine for FX products

Handles
Validation
Lifecycle management
Accounting
Settlement
Reporting & events

Used For
FX Option
ETD
FX Forward
FX Cash

Key Points
Same engine, different product rules
Independent of input (OFS / TIS / UI)
Central focus for automation

One-Line Rule
FXPM = Engine that processes FX trades

| Aspect     | FX Option | ETD       | FXPM        |
| ---------- | --------- | --------- | ----------- |
| Type       | Product   | Product   | Engine      |
| Choice     | Yes       | No        | N/A         |
| Premium    | Yes       | No        | N/A         |
| Margin     | No        | Yes       | Manages     |
| Daily MTM  | No        | Yes       | Executes    |
| Settlement | Optional  | Mandatory | Enforces    |
| Risk       | Limited   | High      | Operational |



******************                         ETD (Exchange-Traded Derivatives)                *************************

ETD are derivative contracts (their value comes from an underlying like stocks, indices, FX, commodities) that are traded on a regulated exchange with standardized terms.
Common ETD types

Futures â€“ obligation to buy/sell at a future date & price
Options â€“ right (not obligation) to buy/sell
Index derivatives â€“ Nifty, S&P 500, FTSE, etc.
Commodity derivatives â€“ Gold, Oil, Agri products

You expect ABC stock to rise next month.
Today price: â‚¹1,000
You buy ABC Futures @ â‚¹1,020 (1-month expiry)
After 1 month:
Price = â‚¹1,080 â†’ Profit = â‚¹60
Price = â‚¹980 â†’ Loss = â‚¹40
You didnâ€™t buy the stock directly; you traded its future price.

ETD trade lifecycle (high level)
Trade placed on exchange
Margin blocked
Trade matched
Clearing house novates (becomes buyer to seller & vice-versa)
Daily MTM (Mark-to-Market)
Expiry / square-off / physical or cash settlement


ETD in banking & trading systems (like T24)
Used for hedging (FX, interest rate, equity risk)
Automated margin, MTM, expiry, settlement
Strong controls & validations â†’ good for STP

ETD = standardized derivative contracts traded on exchanges, cleared by a clearing house, offering transparency, liquidity, and reduced counterparty risk.


