You travel correctly
ğŸ‘‰ Refund = Reverse trade
ğŸ‘‰ New ticket = Rectified trade (Event 300)









 *****************************************************************************************************************************************************

Traditional equity trade
* Buy shares once
* Sell shares once
* Profit/loss depends only on entry & exit

Problem for banks & clients
Clients want regular accumulation
Want discounted buying
Want structured risk
Want automation over time

â¡ï¸ Result: Structured Products

STRUCTURED PRODUCT (SP) -->
A contract that combines derivatives + rules + lifecycle events
It is:
Long-running (weeks/months)
Event-driven
Rule-based
Heavy on valuation, accrual, fixing, maturity
* Accumulator / Decumulator is one type of SP.


Accumulator = agreement to buy shares every working day at a fixed price
Not optional
Not one-time
Obligatory & repeated

Real-life analogy
Imagine:
You promise to buy 10 apples daily
Price fixed at â‚¹50
Market price keeps changing
You must buy anyway
Thatâ€™s an Accumulator.

Decumulator --> Agreement to sell shares every working day at a fixed price

| Term         | Meaning                    |
| ------------ | -------------------------- |
| Underlying   | The share (e.g. Apple)     |
| Strike Price | Fixed agreed price         |
| Market Price | Todayâ€™s live price         |
| Daily Units  | Units per day              |
| Accrual      | Daily obligation recording |
| Fixing       | Settlement checkpoint      |
| Knock-out    | Early termination trigger  |
| Maturity     | Natural end of contract    |

Every working day (COB):
System reads market price
Compares with strike
Calculates accrued units
Updates:ACCRUED.UNITS1


Example
Strike = 50
Market = 45
Daily Units = 100
The customer must buy 100 shares at 50, even though the market is 45
â¡ï¸ Customer is at a loss

GEARING (RISK MULTIPLIER) --> â€œIf market goes against you, buy MORE sharesâ€
This is Gearing Factor
Example
Daily Units = 100
Gearing = 2
Market < Strike
â¡ï¸ Accrued Units = 200

KNOCK-IN & KNOCK-OUT -->
Knock-In
Accrual starts only after price touches a level

Knock-Out
Contract terminates early
No more accrual
Final settlement triggered

Example
Knock-out = 60
Market hits 60
â¡ï¸ Contract ends

Example (Knock-In)
Product setup
Underlying: ABC Stock
Strike: 50
Knock-In level: 55
Accrual: 1 unit per day
Tenor: 10 days

| Day   | Market Price | Accrual               |
| ----- | ------------ | --------------------- |
| Day 1 | 52           | âŒ No (not knocked-in) |
| Day 2 | 54           | âŒ No                  |
| Day 3 | **55**       | âœ… Knock-In triggered  |
| Day 4 | 56           | âœ… 1 unit              |
| Day 5 | 57           | âœ… 1 unit              |

2ï¸âƒ£ Knock-Out (KO)
Meaning:
ğŸ‘‰ If price hits the KO level, the contract ends immediately.

No more accrual.
Settlement happens early.

Example (Knock-Out)
Product setup
Knock-Out level: 60
Accrual per day: 1 unit

| Day   | Market Price | Accrual      |
| ----- | ------------ | ------------ |
| Day 1 | 56           | +1           |
| Day 2 | 58           | +1           |
| Day 3 | **60**       | ğŸš¨ Knock-Out |




FIXING -->
Fixing = periodic settlement checkpoint
â€œOkay, enough accrual â€” now settleâ€

What happens in Fixing?
Accrued units are:
Exercised
Settled (cash / shares)
Residual option expires

Status updated:
FIXED = YES
Each fixing period:
Stored as multi-value set
Cannot be edited after fixing

Why fixing exists?
Avoid waiting till maturity
Reduce risk
Allow partial settlement

Example â€” Accrual Product WITH Fixing
Product setup
Accrual: 1 unit per valid day
Fixing frequency: Monthly
Tenor: 3 months
| Day      | Accrual  |
| -------- | -------- |
| Day 1â€“20 | 20 units |


ğŸ“ Fixing Date (End of Month 1)
âœ” 20 units are:
Exercised
Settled (cash/shares)

Month 2
| Day      | Accrual  |
| -------- | -------- |
| Day 1â€“18 | 18 units |


Month 3
Same logic again.

Fixing 1 â†’ 20 units â†’ FIXED = YES
Fixing 2 â†’ 18 units â†’ FIXED = YES
Fixing 3 â†’ 22 units â†’ FIXED = YES

With fixing:
âœ… Partial settlement
âœ… Risk reduced over time
âœ… Cash flows earlier


ğŸ”° LEVEL 9 â€” UNWIND (EARLY EXIT)
Client can exit:
Fully
Partially

Full Unwind
Contract closed
No future accrual

Partial Unwind
Daily units reduced
Accrual continues on reduced quantity

ğŸ“Œ Important:
Unwind effective date matters
Back-dated unwind needs manual corrections

NOVATION (TRANSFER OF CONTRACT)
What is novation?
Moving the contract from one party to another

Types:
Internal: Client A â†’ Client B (same bank)
External: Client â†’ outside entity
Optional fees apply.


